subSubSection.paragraph:
Structure
: Body robust, relatively large. Head and pronotum shiny. Head with relatively long setae and a 3–4 pairs trichobothrial setae and shallow apodeme depression. Dorsal surface of antenniferes smooth. area from base of clypeus to posterior margin of ocelli without setae. Hairless area forked at basal part of clypeus. Anteocular part of head 3.13–3.4 times as long as postocular part in females and 2.46–2.47 times as long as postocular part in males. Eye narrower than synthlipsis with S-curved posterior margin in lateral view, ocelli large. Scape almost reaching or reaching apex of head, club-shaped, with variably sized (mostly long), erect setae and a few robust, erect setae. Pedicel with dense, adherent, short setae and 6 long trichobothrial setae (
Fig. 169
). Basi- and distiflagellum with short, adherent setae and longer, numerous, regularly arranged, erect setae. Erect setae on basiflagellum of two different lengths. Second visible labial segment reaching or surpassing posterior margin of head. Tranversal furrow of head shallow. Anterior pronotal lobe sculptured with distinct sulci, long and thin apodeme depression, and without collar. Ridges of proepisternum and proepimeron connected in entire length (
Fig. 191
). Transverse suture of pronotum with delicate curvature in middle. Posterior pronotal lobe smooth, slightly depressed medially, at level with curvature of transversal suture. Lateral part of posterior pronotal lobe with distinct, longitudinal, sculpturation. Metapleura with two incomplete ridges. Margins of scutellum thickened and shining with dense, variably sized setae (mostly long setae). Central part of scutellum with distinct granulations. Apex of scutellum short and rounded. Tibia and tarsus with spine-like setae (mostly on inner side). All legs with very long trichobothrial setae. Coxa with long, dense setae. Corium dull with shining basal part and slightly granulated costal margin. Hemelytron with different sized setae, very dense and short on costal margin. Hemelytron surpassing (most of males) or not (females) apex of abdomen. Abdomen ventrally with long and very dense setae, spiracles III–IV placed distant from ventral connexival suture.

Genitalia
: Male—Median process of pygophore (
Fig. 6
), with very small apex (
Fig. 11
). Both parameres (
Figs. 7–10
) slender and club-shaped, slightly curved in middle of length in dorsal view with relatively long setae on outer and inner sides. Vestiture of parameres reaching almost to base. Both parameres with sharp process in apical part. Pedicel of aedeagus long and thin (
Figs. 12, 13
). Dorsal endosomal sclerite distinctly corrugated (
Fig 14
).

Female—Valvifer I quadrangular (
Fig. 5
), on outer side with numerous, dense very short setae and few distinctly longer setae. Styloids on inner margin with dense, short setae and with sharp apical part (
Fig. 3
). Basal part of valvula II with a convolute inward process, forked in apical part with two sharp apices (
Fig. 4
).
